John Edward: Language skills are important for the world’s citizens
Scottish private schools have remained at the top of the academic excellence rankings and this continued in 2018 with the following outstanding exam results, reinforced by personal and collective success in sports, arts, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students studying throughout Scotland, and represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), these schools strive to provide the best service to their students and their parents.
The purpose of private schools is to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen profession and their place as world citizens.
As a sector of education that is able to design and implement a curriculum tailored to the circumstances, we see that modern languages continue to be well-known and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a person in a language that he understands, it comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his native language, it will reach his heart.”
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s recent exam results show that at the top of the tables are the languages with the highest exam pass rate among private schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages scored high A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS schools show that 72 percent of students scored A in Mandarin, 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners, and 63 percent of Spanish learners.
This shows that Scottish private schools support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages that are now among the choices of subjects are included in the curricula of private schools and other schools in the same way as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics).
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills revealed that 17% of respondents found a lack of language skills among the reasons why employers find it difficult to find workers for job vacancies.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future jobs.
As more promising job offers require language skills, such skills are becoming essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career choices made, acquiring a second language will give a person a real advantage in the future, as language skills are lifelong.
The ability to communicate directly with foreign citizens immediately gives a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey conducted in 2013 among more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of respondents do not speak any foreign language well enough to have a conversation about it. The only language with a two-digit percentage of speakers was French with 15 percent.
Therefore, funding language learning is important for today’s children.
Being able to speak several languages, especially those of emerging economies, gives children better opportunities to find a good job.
Different languages are taught in every school in Scotland.
A number of schools focus on classical modern languages, while other schools teach languages that are considered the most important in the UK for 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the child’s interests, private schools always have the option of choosing between several languages taught by experts in their field.
Scottish private schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills to succeed no matter what the future brings.
It can no longer be denied that, in a globalising business environment, languages are crucial for the future of a country, and therefore this must also be reflected in education.
Modern languages should indeed be regarded as "international communication skills".
Private schools continue to offer choice, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Private Schools Council.
