This year, Harvard University is offering a new course in which students need to sleep more to combat the growing aggressive culture of learning through night-long learning marathons that are rich in caffeine.
Students who love the academicism of the best university in the world are often helpless when it comes to the basics of caring for themselves.
Professor Charles Czeisler, a sleep doctor at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, believes this course is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a speech on how sleep disorders affect learning.
“At the end of it, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I being told about this now, in my last year of school?’
“She said no one ever told her the importance of sleep — it made me feel bad,” she told the Telegraph.
The course, which was first introduced to the curriculum this year, explains to students how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic outcomes as well as to improving their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of health at the University, said the university had decided to take a course after it found that students were severely deprived of sleep during the working week.
The one-hour course covers a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books, explaining the effects of caffeine and light, how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance and the importance of the established bedtime practice.
The second part explains to participants how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interacting symbols encourages participants to think about their daily established practice.
“We know that this does not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes," Czeisler added.
According to him, there is still pride in the nocturnal learning marathons, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students means that sleep deprivation is still a growing problem.
“Ensuring adequate quality sleep should be a student’s ‘secret weapon’ to fight stress, exhaustion, and anxiety,” he added. “It even helps against weight gain, as lack of sleep puts the brain into a hunger regime, making the person constantly hungry.”
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemical and physical biology from California, helped Professor Czeisler set up a course after attending one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
Raymond said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to help create a university-wide course.
As a next step, he would like all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining a competing institution.
